<h1 id="secrets"><a id="Secrets"></a>Secrets</h1>

<p>Most of cyber security relies on secrets, but there are some problems with secrets:</p>
<ul>
  <li>ItŌĆÖs impossible to keep a secret secret.</li>
  <li>Once a secret is out, it canŌĆÖt be made secret again.</li>
</ul>

<p>Who do you trust with secrets? A secret getting leaked is invisible, and the longer the list of people who know the secret, the harder it is to figure out who to not trust anymore. -&gt; <strong>if you ACTUALLY want to keep a secret, then donŌĆÖt tell ANYONE!</strong></p>

<p>Best way to keep something secret? Make it no longer a secret or donŌĆÖt have a secret in the first place.</p>

<h3 id="some-problems-that-we-are-faced">Some problems that we are faced</h3>
<ul>
  <li>How can I tell someone some information without others knowing about it? -&gt; <strong>Confidentiality</strong></li>
  <li>How can I pass information around while making sure that it doesnŌĆÖt get tampered with? -&gt; <strong>Integrity</strong></li>
  <li>How can I send information knowing itŌĆÖs going to the right person? -&gt; <strong>Authentication</strong></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="security-by-obscurity">Security by Obscurity</h2>

<p>The problem with secrets, is that most people want information to be kept secret but only if they know the information. The problem with this is that we rely on secrets to keep systems secure, but if the enemy knew everything about the system and still couldnŌĆÖt get in, then the system is far more secure.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>ŌĆ£It must not be required to be secret, and it must be able to fall into the hands of the enemy without inconvenience.ŌĆØ</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In general, your equation of how secure something is should be independent of how obscure any part of it is.</p>

<h2 id="passwords">Passwords</h2>

<p>How can we make sure that the person we want can use a system, but others cannot? Give the user a <strong>key</strong>, which is similar to a secret, but can be changed and is unique to the individual. A password is a kind of key.</p>

<p>Problems with passwords:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Humans are again the weakest link, passwords are usually made to be easily memorable, hence sometimes being a dictionary word</li>
  <li>Passwords can be brute forced</li>
  <li>People reuse passwords</li>
</ul>

